<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Nanhaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Nanhaia" order="Fabales" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Nanhaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with two species, is readily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Wisteriopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Wisteriopsis" order="Fabales" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Wisteriopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the densely pubescent or sericeous ovaries (glabrous in 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Wisteriopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Wisteriopsis" order="Fabales" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Wisteriopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the larger flowers frequently 15-35 mm long (vs 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Wisteriopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Wisteriopsis" order="Fabales" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Wisteriopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
7-15 mm long). In 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Nanhaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Nanhaia" order="Fabales" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Nanhaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the stipules arise immediately above the swollen, hardened gibbosities (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 4. Nanhaia speciosa (Champ. ex Benth.) J. Compton &amp; Schrire. A Habit B flower bud with bract and bracteole C calyx exterior and bracteole D detail of calyx exterior E detail of calyx interior F standard petal G wing petal H keel petal I staminal column J staminal column lateral view K stamen ventral and dorsal view L ovary and style M style and stigma N pod O seed lateral view P seed ventral view (all from Shiu Ling Hu 6091). Drawn by Margaret Tebbs." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.125.34877.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/313260" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
